7.5     [Medium] Inconsistent notesCount handling results in inconsistent results in mul-
             tiple functions
     File(s): NoteAccount.cairo
     Description: In the addNote(...) function the first note of a user gets registered at the notesCount mapping at index 1 and later at the
     notes mapping it uses the same index as the latest notesCount (e.g. 1 for the first note):

1    fn addNote(ref self: ContractState, pubKey: EthAddress, encryptedNote: Span<u256>, msg_hash: u256, r: u256, s: u256, v:
      ↪  u32) {
2        // will panic if the signature is invalid
3        verify_signature(pubKey, msg_hash, r, s, v);
4        self.notesCount.entry(pubKey).write(self.notesCount.read(pubKey) + 1);
 5       self.notes.entry(pubKey).entry(self.notesCount.read(pubKey)).write((*encryptedNote[0], *encryptedNote[1],
          ↪  *encryptedNote[2], *encryptedNote[3], *encryptedNote[4], *encryptedNote[5], *encryptedNote[6]));
6    }

     However, in other functions like getNotes(...) and eraseNotes(...) loops start from index 0 and end when i = notesCount:

1    fn getNotes(self: @ContractState, pubKey: EthAddress) -> Array<(u256, u256, u256, u256, u256, u256, u256)> {
 2       let mut notes: Array = ArrayTrait::<(u256, u256, u256, u256, u256, u256, u256)>::new();
 3       let mut i: u256 = 0;
 4       if(self.notesCount.read(pubKey) == 0){
 5           let mut a: Array = ArrayTrait::<(u256, u256, u256, u256, u256, u256, u256)>::new();
 6           a.append((0,0,0,0,0,0,0));
 7           return a;
 8       }
 9       loop{
10           let note = self.notes.entry(pubKey).entry(i).read();
11           notes.append(note);
12           i+=1;
13           if(self.notesCount.read(pubKey) == i){
14                break;
15           }
16
17       };
18       return notes;
19   }

1    fn eraseNotes(ref self: ContractState, pubKey: EthAddress){
 2       let mut i: u256 = 0;
 3       loop{
 4           self.notes.entry(pubKey).entry(i).write((0,0,0,0,0,0,0));
 5           i+=1;
 6           if(self.notesCount.read(pubKey) == i){
 7               break;
 8           }
 9       };
10   }

     This results on their first iteration being unnecessary since the notes mapping is empty at that index. Also, the loop stops 1 iteration before
     it should, because it doesn’t process the notes mapping at the notesCount index, which stores information. Contradictory to this logic, the
     updateNotes(...) function updates the notes mapping starting from index 0, so getNotes(...) and eraseNotes(...) work correctly for
     notes that have been created through this function:

                                                                                                                                                10
     CODESPECT

1    fn updateNotes(ref self: ContractState,pubKey: EthAddress, msg_hash: u256, r: u256, s: u256, v: u32 ,newNotes:
      ↪  Span<Span<u256>>){
 2         verify_signature(pubKey, msg_hash, r, s, v);
 3         let mut i: u32 = 0;
 4         eraseNotes(ref self,pubKey);
 5         loop{
 6             self.notes.entry(pubKey).entry(i.into()).write((*newNotes[i][0], *newNotes[i][1], *newNotes[i][2],
                ↪  *newNotes[i][3], *newNotes[i][4], *newNotes[i][5], *newNotes[i][6]));
 7             i+=1;
8              if(newNotes.len() == i){
9                  break;
10             }
11        }
12   }

     Impact: The getNotes(...) and eraseNotes(...) will not work correctly for notes that have created using the addNotes(...) function.
     The updateNotes(...) function will also not work correctly since it uses the eraseNotes(...) function itself.
     Recommendation(s): Choose a consistent starting index and use it for all the loops.
     Status: Fixed
     Update from Typhoon: Solved 1fa6a6d6462c66d8ce271b077a0420a7bcbfafdf

7.6     [Medium] Updating the current_day always adds an additional day
     File(s): Pool.cairo
     Description: Deposits and withdrawals always call the updateDay(...) function to check if a day has passed since the storage variable
     current_day. However, if at least a day has passed and current_day needs to be updated, an additional day is always added:

1    fn updateDay(ref self: ContractState) {
 2       let mut cur_day = self.current_day.read();
 3       let mut dif: u256 = 0;
 4       if cur_day < get_block_timestamp().into() {
 5           dif = get_block_timestamp().into() - cur_day;
 6           if dif > day.into() {
 7               let days = getDaysPassed(@cur_day);
 8               self.current_day.write(cur_day + (day.into() * days) + day.into()); // @audit-issue an additional day gets
                  ↪  added
 9           }
10       }
11   }

     Impact: Inaccurate tracking of the days, since every time the current_day gets updated, an additional day gets added.
     Recommendation(s): Remove the + day.into() part of the calculation.
     Status: Fixed
     Update from Typhoon: Solved 1fa6a6d6462c66d8ce271b077a0420a7bcbfafdf

